               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-400-person2076">
                  JOHN 
                  DEEKER
               <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2076" type="surname" value="DEEKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2076" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2076" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am porter to Mr. George Noah, a <rs id="t18260914-400-viclabel2251" type="occupation">tailor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-400-victim2075 t18260914-400-viclabel2251"></join> and <rs id="t18260914-400-viclabel2252" type="occupation">breeches maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-400-victim2075 t18260914-400-viclabel2252"></join>, who lives in <placeName id="t18260914-400-crimeloc2253">Pall Mall</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-400-crimeloc2253" type="placeName" value="Pall Mall"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-400-crimeloc2253" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-400-off2248 t18260914-400-crimeloc2253"></join>, in the parish of St. James, Westminster. On the 21st of August I was coming up from the kitchen to the shop, to speak to my master, and saw the prisoner in the shop, in the act of taking a piece of cloth; I asked the foreman if he had given a piece of cloth to any body - he said No; I pursued the prisoner, who had the cloth in his possession; I saw him stopped, without losing sight of him, and saw him throw it away - I took it up, and the foreman took him, in my presence.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by Mr. PRENDERGAST. Q. What time was this? A. A quarter past eight o'clock; our shop door was shut, but not locked.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-400-person2077">
                  PHILIP 
                  HARROW
               <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2077" type="surname" value="HARROW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2077" type="given" value="PHILIP"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2077" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 21st of August I was foreman to George Noah. I heard a man had run away with a piece of cloth; I followed, and saw the prisoner was carrying it in a way to conceal it. I saw him throw it away; the porter took it up; I took the prisoner at the corner - the cloth is worth 18l.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Where were you? A. I was gone up to the workshop - when I came down the porter gave me information. I did not see the prisoner in the shop - when I first saw him he was turning the corner of Crown-court, about forty yards off, walking briskly.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Had you seen the cloth that day? A. Yes - I had been cutting it a quarter of an hour before. The shop is a part of the dwelling-house - it is under the first floor.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-400-person2078">
                  JAMES 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2078" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2078" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-400-person2078" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I took the prisoner. and bring the cloth here.(Property produced and sworn to).</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The witness said he saw me take the cloth off the counter, and go up the court; I had got to the top of the court when the foreman came out, and he lost sight of me; Mr. Noah wished to let me go, and several persons wished to liberate me, and the foreman would not let me go.</p>
               <p>PHILIP HARROW re-examined. Q. Were there any other persons about who wished you to let him go? A. There was a Jew, who came up, and said Mr. Noah wished me to let him go, but I took him back.</p>
